.TH KEYSTASH 1 "July 2026" "keystash 0.4.3" "keystash User Manual"
.SH NAME
keystash \- Secure offline TUI and CLI password manager written in Rust
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B keystash
[\-\-no\-sync] [tui|init|add|list|search|show|copy|generate|import|export|delete|reset|sync|help]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B keystash
is a lightweight, secure, and completely offline password manager. It features an interactive Terminal User Interface (TUI) built on Ratatui, secure Argon2id key derivation, column-level XChaCha20-Poly1305 AEAD encryption, unencrypted Bitwarden JSON importing, and two-way logical git database synchronization.
.PP
Running
.B keystash
without any commands launches the interactive TUI.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-no\-sync
Bypass all Git synchronization processes (startup pull, database updates thread, and exit push). Useful for offline access or slow connections.
.TP
.B \-\-profile \fIname\fR, \-P \fIname\fR
Use a fully separate vault profile: its own vault.db, config.json, and git repository/remote, stored under ~/.config/keystash/profiles/\fIname\fR/. Works with every command and the TUI (the lock screen shows the active profile). Names are restricted to letters, digits, '-' and '_'. Each profile syncs independently -- run "keystash \-\-profile \fIname\fR sync setup" to configure its remote. The default vault (no flag) is untouched by profiles.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B init
Initialize a new local password vault database and configure your Master Password.
.TP
.B add \fItitle\fR \fItags\fR \fIusername\fR [\fIurl\fR]
Insert a new credential. Tags are comma-separated (e.g. "work,email") and are normalized before storing (trimmed, deduplicated). The CLI will securely prompt you for your password. Double quotes are required for arguments containing spaces or commas (e.g. keystash add "My Google Account" "email, personal" "user@gmail.com").
.TP
.B list [\-r|\-\-reveal]
List all stored credentials in the vault. Passwords are masked by default unless \-r or \-\-reveal is supplied. WARNING: Revealing all passwords dumps them in plaintext into the terminal scrollback buffer. Use with caution.
.TP
.B search \fIquery\fR [\-r|\-\-reveal]
Search for matching credentials across titles, tags, usernames, or URLs. Passwords are masked by default unless \-r or \-\-reveal is supplied. A query starting with a dash is matched literally as long as it isn't \-r/\-\-reveal itself; use "keystash search \-\- \-yourquery" if it collides with a flag name.
.TP
.B show \fIid\fR [\-r|\-\-reveal]
Show a detailed view of a secret (including notes). Passwords and notes are masked by default unless \-r or \-\-reveal is supplied.
.TP
.B copy \fIid\fR [\fIusername\fR|\fIpassword\fR|\fIurl\fR]
Copy the target secret field to the system clipboard (automatically clearing it after the configured delay, default 5 seconds). Defaults to copying the password.
.TP
.B generate [\-l \fIlength\fR] [\-\-words [\fIn\fR]] [\-\-no\-uppercase] [\-\-no\-numbers] [\-\-no\-symbols] [\-\-save]
Generate a random secure password (excluding ambiguous characters) and copy it to the clipboard for the configured delay. Length is clamped to 4\-256. With \-\-words [n], generates a diceware passphrase instead: n words (3\-12, default 6) drawn from the embedded EFF large wordlist, hyphen-joined -- the better choice for anything typed or memorized (6 words is about 77 bits of entropy). Charset options apply to this run only unless \-\-save is passed.
.TP
.B import \fIpath/to/backup_file\fR
Import login credentials from unencrypted files (supports Bitwarden JSON, KeyStash CSV, Brave/Chrome CSV, Firefox CSV, LastPass CSV, KeePassXC CSV, and 1Password CSV).
.TP
.B export \fIpath/to/output_file.csv\fR
Export all vault credentials to an unencrypted CSV file (with permissions restricted to 0600 on Unix).
.TP
.B delete \fIid\fR
Delete a credential record by its database ID.
.TP
.B reset
Nuke the local database file after confirming via a verification prompt.
.TP
.B sync
Force a manual logical merge and synchronization with your configured Git remote.
.TP
.B sync setup
Interactive one-time sync setup. Detects whether this is the first device (a local vault exists and gets pushed as the initial backup) or an additional device (the vault is pulled from the remote), asks for the remote URL, writes the .gitignore, sets a repo-local git identity if none is configured, and verifies the remote is reachable. Works with any git remote: a private GitHub/GitLab repo, an SSH-reachable machine (you@server:vault.git), or a bare repo on a filesystem path such as a NAS mount (/mnt/nas/vault.git). Never needs the master password.
.TP
.B change-password
Change Master Password and re-encrypt all stored vault secrets using a newly derived key.
.TP
.B help, -h, --help
Show the standard command-line help block.
.SH TUI KEYBINDINGS
Within the interactive dashboard, use the following keys:
.TP
.B Tab / Shift+Tab
Cycle focus forward/backward between the Tags list, Credentials list, and Details pane.
.TP
.B Arrow Up / Down
Scroll through lists item-by-item.
.TP
.B PageUp / PageDown
Scroll lists page-by-page.
.TP
.B Space
Mark or unmark a credential for mass actions.
.TP
.B / (Slash)
Focus the search bar to filter credentials by query text. Press Enter or Esc to exit search entry.
.TP
.B a
Add a new credential.
.TP
.B e
Edit the selected credential.
.TP
.B d
Delete the selected credential (or all marked credentials if any exist).
.TP
.B v
Toggle password and notes plaintext visibility in the Details pane.
.TP
.B c
Copy username to clipboard (clears automatically in configured delay, default 5s).
.TP
.B p
Copy decrypted password to clipboard (clears automatically in configured delay, default 5s).
.TP
.B u
Copy website URL to clipboard (clears automatically in configured delay, default 5s).
.TP
.B m
Open the Change Master Password form overlay.
.TP
.B s
Force a manual sync with the configured Git remote. Runs the same conflict detection as the automatic post-unlock sync, and works even when the Auto Sync setting is off.
.TP
.B i
Open the Import modal popup to import credentials from unencrypted backups.
.TP
.B x
Open the Export modal popup to export credentials (all or selected) to an unencrypted CSV.
.TP
.B h
Check the selected password (or marked passwords if any exist) on HaveIBeenPwned.
.TP
.B H
Check all passwords in the vault on HaveIBeenPwned asynchronously in a background thread.
.TP
.B D
Open the duplicate credential detector and interactive resolver.
.TP
.B ,
Open the KeyStash settings screen modal.
.TP
.B ?
Toggle the Help & Keybindings modal popup.
.TP
.B Esc
Cancel dialogs, close forms, or exit the application.
.TP
.B q
Same as Esc, except in text-entry fields (Add/Edit form, Change Password, Settings), where it types the letter instead.
.SH TAGS
Each credential carries one or more comma-separated tags (e.g. "work, email"). The TUI sidebar lists every tag individually and filters on any of them; tags are normalized on save (trimmed, deduplicated). Tags are stored in the same database field older KeyStash versions treat as the single category, so vaults, CSV exports, and shared Git remotes remain fully compatible in both directions.
.SH SYNCHRONIZATION & MULTI-MACHINE SETUP
If the config folder (~/.config/keystash) is initialized as a Git repository, keystash will automatically synchronize and merge database updates across your machines.
.PP
The settings screen's Auto Sync toggle controls only the automatic sync actions (startup fetch, post-unlock/post-import merge, exit-time push); with it off, the manual [s] key and "keystash sync" still work on demand. The \-\-no\-sync flag is stronger and disables all sync, manual included, for that session. The outcome of every background sync is reported in the TUI: success in the status bar, failures (including a refused push after a master-password rotation performed elsewhere) in a dialog with recovery instructions.
.PP
Syncs are cheap when nothing changed: after the fetch, if the remote's commit equals the local one and the vault file is untouched, the sync ends there -- no merge work, no push -- and quitting a session that modified nothing skips the exit-time sync entirely. The .gitignore written in the setup steps below is created automatically on the first sync if missing (an existing customized one is never touched).
.PP
Optional history retention: encrypted vaults do not delta-compress, so every pushed change stores a full copy and the remote grows without bound by default. The settings screen's "History Keep" field (0 = keep everything, minimum 10 when enabled) squashes history older than the newest N snapshots after each push and force-pushes with \-\-force\-with\-lease, so a concurrent push from another device always wins. Older snapshots are also the rollback archive -- hence opt-in. A device that last synced before a squash still merges safely; it only loses its 3-way conflict base for that one sync. Branch protection on the vault repo blocks the force-push and must be off if retention is enabled.
.PP
.B First-time Setup (Device A):
.nf
  cd ~/.config/keystash
  git init
  echo "*" > .gitignore
  echo "!vault.db" >> .gitignore
  git remote add origin <private-git-repo-url>
  git branch -M main
  git add .
  git commit -m "Initial vault backup"
  git push -u origin main
.fi
.PP
.B Adding a New Device (Device B):
.IP
.B WARNING:
DO NOT run "keystash init" on a secondary device. This will generate a different database salt and result in decryption errors. Instead, pull the existing database directly from origin:
.nf
  mkdir -p ~/.config/keystash
  cd ~/.config/keystash
  git init
  echo "*" > .gitignore
  echo "!vault.db" >> .gitignore
  git remote add origin <private-git-repo-url>
  git branch -M main
  git pull origin main
.fi
.SH SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
.B Layered Encryption (Full Database + Sensitive Fields)
.IP
The entire vault.db file is encrypted with SQLCipher: schema, indexes, and every column, including title, category (the column tags are stored in), username, url, and timestamps. Nothing in the file is readable without the master password—including by anyone with read access to your private Git backup repository. As defense in depth, the password and notes fields are additionally encrypted with XChaCha20-Poly1305 under an independently derived key, so a compromise of the SQLCipher layer alone does not expose them. The Argon2id salt is embedded in the first 16 bytes of vault.db (it is not secret on its own); vaults created before v0.3.6 kept it in a vault.salt sidecar file and are converted automatically on first unlock.
.PP
.B Clipboard Security
.IP
KeyStash automatically clears copied credentials from the system clipboard after the configured delay (default 5 seconds). However, third-party clipboard history managers (like CopyQ or Klipper) can intercept and save copied text. You should configure these managers to ignore copy actions from the "keystash" binary.
.PP
.B Memory Cleansing
.IP
Master passwords and decryption keys are securely zeroized from RAM after use. TUI buffers are pre-allocated and cleared/zeroized in-place to prevent heap reallocation remnants. Locking the vault also drops the open, keyed SQLCipher connection itself, not just the in-memory key, so the vault's encrypted contents aren't left readable through a lingering connection while on the Lock screen.
.PP
.B Schema Migrations
.IP
Database schema integrity checks and upgrades are performed automatically on startup using a custom embedded migrations mechanism.
.PP
.B Deletion Tombstone Pruning
.IP
Deleting a credential leaves a tombstone record behind so the deletion propagates correctly to other devices on their next sync. Tombstones older than 90 days are pruned automatically during sync, so a deleted credential's title and username don't live on in the vault forever; the 90-day window is intentionally generous, giving an infrequently-synced device time to see the deletion before its tombstone disappears.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/keystash/vault.db
The local SQLite database storing metadata, validation tokens, and your encrypted secrets.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B KEYSTASH_CONFIG_DIR
If set, names the directory vault.db and config.json live in directly (no keystash/ subdirectory is appended), overriding XDG_CONFIG_HOME and HOME entirely. Primarily an isolation seam for tests and unusual setups.
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
If set, used to locate the config directory as $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/keystash/ instead of the default. Checked before HOME.
.TP
.B HOME
Used to locate the user's config directory (~/.config/keystash/) when XDG_CONFIG_HOME is not set. If neither is set, KeyStash falls back to ./.config/keystash/ relative to the current directory and prints a warning.
